Indian Stocks Drop for Fifth Day as Factory Output Growth Slows

-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 
2011-04-11T10:08:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-11/indian-stocks-drop-for-fifth-day-as-factory-output-growth-slows.html
India ’s stocks dropped for a fifth
day, the longest stretch of losses in more than two months, as
the nation’s industrial production growth unexpectedly slowed
and commodity costs climbed.  Tata Motors Ltd. (TTMT) , the country’s biggest truckmaker, fell to
a two-week low. Output at factories, utilities and mines rose
3.6 percent in February from a year ago, the government said
today. The median estimate of 30 economists in a Bloomberg News
survey was for a 5.1 percent climb. S&P’s GSCI Index of 24
commodities climbed 2.1 percent on April 8, a seventh day of
gains. Oil jumped 4.5 percent last week.  Housing Development
Finance Corp. (HDFC)  declined the most in almost a month.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, lost
208.86, or 1.1 percent, to 19,242.59, according to preliminary
closing prices at 3:30 p.m. in Mumbai. The S&P CNX Nifty Index
on the National Stock Exchange dropped 1.1 percent to 5,779.50.
The BSE 200 Index fell 1 percent to 2,378.17. The markets are
closed tomorrow for a public holiday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Rajhkumar K Shaaw in Mumbai at 
